The stress of trying to work full time remotely while also managing childcare and remote schooling of my children (ages 11 and 13) is extremely challenging. This is a burden that is falling more on women than men, even when both partners in the marriage are working full time remotely. This burden is significant and unmeasured here. Some school systems are requiring essentially the same volume of work be completed and graded (which will go on record for the children) remotely. I am concerned that your questions do not ask about children in the home requiring attention. How many children under 12 does not capture information about children 13 to 18 who also require considerable attention. They are also much more aware of what is happening and many are experiencing distress that parents need to attend to.   It is also important to consider the quality of the relationships that are in the home where people are isolated. These are the primary relationships that are being leveraged. Sometimes this will improve connections and relationships may be enhanced, but other times this could cause more strain.   The stress of isolation will also cause significant anxiety and depression. Consider asking about this.
